Step 1: Observe and simplify the first radical
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{4+\sqrt{8+4c}} &= \sqrt{4+\sqrt{4\cdot2+4c}} & \text{(Expressing 8 as } 4\cdot2 \text{)}\\
&= \sqrt{4+\sqrt{4\cdot(2+c)}} & \text{(Factoring out the common factor 4)}\\
&= \sqrt{4+2\sqrt{2+c}} & \text{(Taking the square root of 4 inside the radical)}\\
&= \sqrt{2\cdot(2+2\sqrt{2+c})} & \text{(Combining terms under one radical)}\\
&= \sqrt{2}\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2+c}} & \text{(Using the property that } \sqrt{a}\sqrt{b} = \sqrt{a\cdot b} \text{)}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Combine like terms and begin to solve
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{2}\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2+c}}+ \sqrt{2+\sqrt{2+c}} &= 2+2\sqrt{2} & \text{(Original equation)}\\
(\sqrt{2} + 1)\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2+c}} &= 2+2\sqrt{2} & \text{(Factoring out the common term)}\\
(1+\sqrt{2})\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2+c}} &= 2(1+\sqrt{2}) & \text{(Rewriting right-hand side as } 2 \text{ times } (1+\sqrt{2}) \text{)}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Continue solving for $c$
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{2+\sqrt{2+c}} &= 2 & \text{(Dividing both sides by } (1+\sqrt{2}) \text{)}\\
2+\sqrt{2+c} &= 4 & \text{(Squaring both sides to remove the square root)}\\
\sqrt{2+c} &= 2 & \text{(Subtracting 2 from both sides)}\\
2+c &= 4 & \text{(Squaring both sides to remove the square root again)}\\
c &= 2 & \text{(Subtracting 2 from both sides)}
\end{align*}

Final Answer: 2.0

