Begin by isolating the radical on one side of the equation:
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{2x^2+1}&=\sqrt{19}
\end{align*}

Proceed by squaring both sides of the equation to eliminate the square roots:
\begin{align*}
(\sqrt{2x^2+1})^2&=(\sqrt{19})^2 \\
2x^2+1&=19
\end{align*}

Next, subtract 1 from both sides to set up the equation for factoring:
\begin{align*}
2x^2+1-1&=19-1 \\
2x^2&=18
\end{align*}

Divide both sides by 2 to solve for $x^2$:
\begin{align*}
\frac{2x^2}{2}&=\frac{18}{2} \\
x^2&=9
\end{align*}

Find the square root of both sides to find the values of $x$:
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{x^2}&=\sqrt{9} \\
x&=\pm3
\end{align*}

Identify the possible values for $x$, which are $x=3$ and $x=-3$.

Finally, calculate the average of the two values by summing them up and dividing by the number of values:
\begin{align*}
\text{Average} &= \frac{3 + (-3)}{2} \\
\text{Average} &= \frac{0}{2} \\
\text{Average} &= 0
\end{align*}

Therefore the average of all possible values of $x$ is $\boxed{0}$.

