answer:
Apply Simon's Favorite Factoring Trick by rearranging the equations to isolate the constants on one side:
\begin{align*}
xy + 2x + 3y &= 6,\\
yz + 4y + 2z &= 6,\\
xz + 4x + 3z &= 30,
\end{align*}
Add a suitable constant to both sides of each equation to complete the squares:
\begin{align*}
xy + 2x + 3y + 6 &= 12, \text{ by adding } 6,\\
yz + 4y + 2z + 8 &= 14, \text{ by adding } 8,\\
xz + 4x + 3z + 12 &= 42, \text{ by adding } 12,
\end{align*}
Factor the left-hand sides to reveal products of binomials:
\begin{align*}
(x+3)(y+2) &= 12,\\
(y+2)(z+4) &= 14,\\
(x+3)(z+4) &= 42,
\end{align*}
Observe that taking the product of all three factored equations yields:
\begin{align*}
[(x+3)(y+2)(z+4)]^2 &= 12 \cdot 14 \cdot 42,\\
&= 2^4 \cdot 3^2 \cdot 7^2,
\end{align*}
Take the square root of each side to eliminate the exponent:
\begin{align*}
(x+3)(y+2)(z+4) &= \pm \sqrt{2^4 \cdot 3^2 \cdot 7^2},\\
&= \pm 2^2 \cdot 3 \cdot 7,
\end{align*}
Recall the individual binomial product that captured $y$ and $z$ was equal to 14:
\begin{align*}
(y+2)(z+4) = 14,
\end{align*}
Relate this product to the overall product to solve for the remaining variable, $x$:
\begin{align*}
14(x+3) = (y+2)(z+4)(x+3) &= \pm 2^2 \cdot 3 \cdot 7,
\end{align*}
Solve for $x+3$ by comparing the coefficients of the two expressions:
\begin{align*}
x+3 &= \pm 6,
\end{align*}
Identify that among the two possible solutions for $x+3$, only one is positive:
\begin{align*}
x+3 &= 6 \text{ (since we seek the positive solution for } x\text{)},
\end{align*}
Isolate $x$ by subtracting 3 from both sides:
\begin{align*}
x &= 6 - 3,
\end{align*}
Conclude that the positive solution for $x$ is:
\begin{align*}
x &= 3.
\end{align*}
Final Answer: 3.0

